{{refimprove|date=January 2013}}
A '''novelette''' is "a short piece of [[Lyric poetry|lyrical]] music, especially one for the [[piano]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collinsdictionary.com/dictionary/english/novelette|title=Definition of novelette|work=Collins English Dictionary|publisher=Collins|accessdate=20 January 2013}}</ref>

The word was used by the composer [[Robert Schumann]] as a title for some piano pieces, a choice that reflected his literary background and interests. The music in question (op. 21, and op. 99 no. 9) is episodic, however, and does not especially resemble a narrative. The name may also allude to [[Clara Novello]].<ref name="Ostwald1987">{{cite book|last=Ostwald|first=Peter F.|title=Schumann: The Inner Voices of a Musical Genius|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yVTo_GHbihoC&pg=PA138|accessdate=20 January 2013|date=1987-03-02|publisher=UPNE|isbn=9781555530143|page=138}}</ref>

Schumann was followed by [[Niels Gade]], [[Theodor Kirchner]], [[Stephen Heller]] and much later by [[Francis Poulenc|Poulenc]] (''[[Trois novelettes (Poulenc)|Trois novelettes]]''), [[Witold Lutosławski|Lutosławski]] ("Novelette for Orchestra"), [[Cécile Chaminade|Chaminade]], [[Alexander Tcherepnin|Tcherepnin]], [[Josef Tal]] and [[George Gershwin]] ("Novelette in Fourths").

